I also have Galaxy Note 9 like Rob Carpenter and I have no issues with export however it was a bit learning curve to figure out what type of export fits my needs. Now I am using mostly E2 which holds basically all available data and then I import the table as a new list to LibreOffice Calc. I use the table the other way around, so the only issue is that I have to swap rows for columns, which could be on of the options available in the export already, that's my only point here. Otherwise I think one missing part is the absence of PC version or at least Web based access to the database, so one could do certain operations more comfortably on the bigger screen. In such case it would need the database to be on a server, and that's my another point - I have Qnap Server at home and I would love to have this app working with database on my own server. That would be really great!

I provide field services at customer sites, and this app makes it simple to keep track of time on site and services performed with just a few taps. Reporting makes it equally easy to get summary information for invoicing.  Custom fields allow me to track client name independent of the task.  Tasker integration is great - allowing me to: automatically add calendar event title, location and notes to a task when I check-in; remind me to checkout or change task when connecting to my truck's Bluetooth, log phone calls while checked in (the DynamicG plugin does work reliably).  Automatic export to Google Calendar makes for easy viewing of data on my PC and other mobile devices where the app is not installed.  The only thing missing for me now is an incremental sync option - so I can view data in the app on multiple devices without having to update ALL of the data with each change.

Have you ever had a "I know I worked a lot but I don't know where my time went" kind of moment? For me, that was every day juggling multiple tasks. Not any more.  I am an internal consultant. I need to report my time monthly. I used to go through my calendar and email every month to see, day by day the core tasks where I spent my time. it would take me about 4 hours to sort that out.  Now I just Check in when I get in, click "switch task" every time I will do something else. Check out for lunch, check in after, and check out at the end of the day. At the end of the month I generate a report and transfer the consolidated times to my company's time reporting app. in 20 minutes I'm done.  Some days I forget to check in. No problem, I check in and change the time to the actual time.  It saves me a ton of time and I know I am accurate in my reporting.
